    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Saving Literary Gems</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>National Endowment for Humanities Chmn William R Ferris letter calls for increase in agency's budget</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Scholarly Editions in Jeopardy'' (editorial, Oct. 21):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Scholarly Editions in Jeopardy'' (editorial, Oct. 21):</p>
        <p>Our struggle to rebuild the budget of the National Endowment for the Humanities comes at a time when every sector of America's humanities community is strained financially. For the last two years we have considered how best to use our limited funds to support as many scholarly editions as possible. Several options are now under consideration.</p>
        <p>No matter what course the N.E.H. chooses, the reality is that these editions, like all of America's humanities needs, are threatened by the N.E.H.'s diminished budget. I continue to believe that the wealthiest country in history can invest more in the papers of great Americans, in classroom teaching, in museum and library resources, and in public radio and TV programs. These are national resources that enrich Americans of all ages, and we will surely be judged by future generations on their neglect.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM R. FERRIS  Chairman, National Endowment for the Humanities  Washington, Oct. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
